### NuGet Product Used

NuGet SDK

### Product Version

6.6.0

### Worked before?

_No response_

### Impact

It's more difficult to complete my work

### Repro Steps & Context

Accessing `HttpResponseMessage.RequestMessage.Content.SerializeToStream()` in the delegate passed to `HttpSource.ProcessResponseAsync` throws a `NullReferenceException`. This makes it harder to provide diagnostic logging on the HTTP session (i.e. logging request and response). A workaround I found is rerunning the `HttpRequestMessage` factory to get another copy of the request. This feels wrong since this pattern is quite possible with vanilla `HttpClient` as shown in the sample below. Also, an NRE feels wrong :)

Here is a full repro:
```csharp
using NuGet.Common;
using NuGet.Protocol;
using NuGet.Protocol.Core.Types;

// HttpClient -- works
using var httpClient = new HttpClient();
var response = await httpClient.SendAsync(new HttpRequestMessage(HttpMethod.Delete, "https://www.nuget.org/api/v2/package/Knapcode.TorSharp/2.14.0")
{
    Content = new StringContent("some content"),
});
Console.WriteLine("HttpClient: " + await response.RequestMessage!.Content!.ReadAsStringAsync());

// NuGet client SDK -- throws NRE
using var cache = new SourceCacheContext();
var repository = Repository.Factory.GetCoreV3("https://api.nuget.org/v3/index.json");
var resource = await repository.GetResourceAsync<HttpSourceResource>();

var requestBody = await resource.HttpSource.ProcessResponseAsync(
    new HttpSourceRequest(() => new HttpRequestMessage(HttpMethod.Delete, "https://www.nuget.org/api/v2/package/Knapcode.TorSharp/2.14.0")
    {
        Content = new StringContent("some content"),
    }),
    async response =>
    {
        return await response.RequestMessage!.Content!.ReadAsStringAsync();
    },
    NullLogger.Instance,
    CancellationToken.None);

Console.WriteLine("NuGet client SDK: " + requestBody);
```

